eden","1089–Male":"1089–Overleden","1136":"1136","Abt 1133":"circa 1133","Aft 1178":"na 1178","1178":"1178","1089":"1089","1210":"1210","1133":"1133","1180":"1180","Bowsley, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1133–Aft 1178":"about 1133–after 1178","1133–1178":"1133–1178","1136–Male":"1136–Deceased","1178–1210":"1178–1210","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1089–Male":"1089–Deceased","1136":"1136","Abt 1133":"about 1133","Aft 1178":"after 1178","1178":"1178","1089":"1089","1210":"1210","1133":"1133","1180":"1180","Bowsley, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Glanville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): of Norman origin, a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, named from an ancient Germanic personal name of uncertain form and meaning + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. This name has frequently been confused with <b>Glanfield</b>, a habitational name from Glanvill Farm in Devon, Clanville in Somerset and Hampshire, or Clanfield in Hampshire, or from some other place likewise named with Old English <i>clǣne</i> ‘clean’ (i.e. free of brambles and undergrowth) + <i>feld</i> ‘pasture, open country’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Glanville was born about 1133, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Harvey de Glanville. He had at least 2 daughters. He died after 1178, in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1133–Aft 1178":"umbes 1133–pärast 1178","1133–1178":"1133–1178","1136–Male":"1136–Surnud","1178–1210":"1178–1210","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1089–Male":"1089–Surnud","1136":"1136","Abt 1133":"umbes 1133","Aft 1178":"pärast 1178","1178":"1178","1089":"1089","1210":"1210","1133":"1133","1180":"1180","Bowsley, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1133–Aft 1178":"noin 1133–1178 jälkeen","1133–1178":"1133–1178","1136–Male":"1136–Kuollut","1178–1210":"1178–1210","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1089–Male":"1089–Kuollut","1136":"1136","Abt 1133":"noin 1133","Aft 1178":"1178 jälkeen","1178":"1178","1089":"1089","1210":"1210","1133":"1133","1180":"1180","Bowsley, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr"